chronology.CE_summary: Birth of Vladimir Vladimirovič Sofronickij (1901∘ – 1961†) and his twin sister, Vera Vladimirovna (1901∘ – 1948†), in Sankt-Peterburg. Their father, Vladimir Nikolaevič (1869∘ – 1942†), was a professor of mathematics and physics. Their mother, Vera Aleksandrovna (1875∘ – 1935†), came from the Borovikovskij family, famous in the field of arts, in poetry and painting. Their brother and three sisters, all older than them, are: Nikolaj Vladimirovič, Ol’ga Vladimirovna (1893∘ – 1933†), Natal’ja Vladimirovna (1897∘ – 1979†), Elena Vladimirovna (1898∘ – 1986†).
The Sofronickij family settled in Warszawa, where the father, Vladimir Nikolaevič, was appointed inspector for a school district (see Artese 2000, p. 84).

Vladimir Sofronickij studied, for several months, with “the composer Ruzicki, father of the well-known Polish pianist” (Vicinskij 2008). According to Voskobojnikov (2016), it is in reality Aleksander Różycki, pianist and professor at the Warszawa Conservatory, father of the Polish composer Ludomir Różycki (1883∘ – 1953†). Nekrasova (2008, p. 134, 138 and 148) confirms that this is indeed Aleksander Różycki, whose published method places great importance on rhythm and rhythmic combinations, based on his own arrangements of popular works and Polish folklore.

Started piano studies with Anna Lebedeva-Gecevič in Warszawa. Anna Lebedeva-Gecevič is a Russian pianist who studied with Nikolaj Grigor'evič Rubinštejn at the Moskva Conservatory; she is the mother of pianist Vsevolod Ivanovič Bujukli. The exact date of August 29 is mentioned by Nekrasova (2008, p. 135) for the start of classes. A notebook with the transcription of the lessons of the first eighteen months of his classes with Anna Lebedeva-Gecevič was offered, as a token of friendship, by Vladimir Sofronickij to Ekaterina Daugovet (1882∘ – 1942†), and found in 1978, well after her death during the siege of Leningrad (see Nekrasova 2008, p. 135-136).

Discovery of the music of composer Aleksandr Skrjabin through the score of his Prelude for the left hand in C sharp minor, opus 9 no. 1; young Sofronickij calls him Skrjabinov [sic] in a letter to his older sister Natal’ja (see Juban 1998, p. 55).

During a concert of young students of Anna Lebedeva-Gecevič, at their teacher's home, Vladimir Sofronickij plays a Song by Mendelssohn-Bartholdy and an Irish Air by Hertz (see Nekrasova 2008, p. 136).

During an evening in the entourage (Gercog) of the family of the poet Aleksandr Blok, rue de la Montagne, in Warszawa, the young Sofronickij plays in front of Blok, whom he will only meet, according to his own expression, “after [Blok’s] death” (see Voskobojnikov 2009a, p. 392-393). Blok had come to attend the funeral of his father, Aleksandr L'vovič, in Warszawa, and had stayed there from December 1 to 18, 1909: see Mil'štejn (1982a, p. 432-433) and Nekrasova (2008, p. 136-139). The poet Ekaterina Gercog (1884∘ – >1955†) witnessed this meeting of the young Vladimir Sofronickij with Aleksandr Blok. Blok's notebooks mention an evening with the Gercogs on December 15, 1909, but it is possible that the poet did not take notes about his other possible visits to the Gercogs, which is why this date remains uncertain (see Nekrasova 2008, p. 137). It was only much later, in Petrograd, that Ekaterina Gercog linked, for Vladimir Sofronickij, the poet he had discovered and loved and the man for whom he had once played the piano in Warszawa, when he was a child. According to Evans (2008, p. 14), Aleksandr Blok partly wrote his poem Весенний день прошел без дела while Vladimir Sofronickij played; in any case, Ekaterina Gercog gave him the autograph of this poem that Aleksandr Blok had written to her as a souvenir on stamped paper (see Nekrasova 2008, p. 137).

chronology.venue: salle du gouvernement régional (ou de l’hôtel de ville)
chronology.CE_summary: First appearance in public during an evening given by the pupils and students of the pianist Anna Lebedeva-Gecevič and the singer V. M. Svjatlovskaja. Service criticized in the press 2.

Brief trip of the Sofronickij family to Sankt-Peterburg, during which Vladimir is introduced to Aleksandr Glazunov, the Russian singer (bass) and teacher Stanislav Ivanovič Gabel’ (1849∘ – 1924†) and the Russian composer and music critic Cezar’ Antonovič Kjui (Cui) (1835∘ – 1918†), at the conservatory of the city. At the end of this interview, Glazunov advised the Sofronickij couple to entrust the continuation of their younger son's musical studies to the pianist and teacher Aleksandr Michalovskij, in Warszawa. Vladimir Sofronickij was nevertheless immediately eligible for the Sankt-Peterburg conservatory, after this interview, but since his father could not move his family immediately, it was decided in the meantime to follow the second option of Aleksandr Glazunov and to choose this great piano teacher in Warszawa. See V. N. Sofronickij (1982, p. 21-22) and Nekrasova (2008, p. 140).

Start of piano lessons with Aleksandr Michalovskij in Warszawa, at the School of the City Music Society. Aleksandr Michalovskij is a former student of Ignaz Moscheles, Carl Reinecke and especially Theodor Coccius at the Leipzig Conservatory, in the lineages of Chopin and Beethoven. He also became a friend of Karol Mikuli, a student of Fryderyk Chopin, and he was able to meet Princess Marceline Czartoryska (née Radziwiłł), a student of Carl Czerny and Fryderyk Chopin. Aleksandr Michalovskij's first reaction to Vladimir Sofronickij and his mother was to indicate that he did not work with children, but he became very enthusiastic after listening to the nine-year-old boy's playing (see Nekrasova 2008, p. 140). Three years of lessons begin, during which Vladimir Sofronickij, on the advice of his teacher, can also listen in concert, at the Warszawa Philharmonic, to musicians such as Sergej Rachmaninoff, Vsevolod Bujukli, Konstantin Igumnov, Nikolaj Andreevič Orlov, Aleksandr Michalovskij himself, Irina Èneri (Gorjainova) and the Poles Stanislav Barcevič and Iosif Adamovič Turčinskij, as well as conductors like Vasilij Il’ič Safonov and Gžegož (Grigorij) Fitel’berg. He also met the tenor of the Milan opera, G. Genzardi. See V. N. Sofronickij (1982, p. 23).

The Sofronickij family returned to Sankt-Peterburg, but young Vladimir nevertheless continued his lessons with Michalovskij in Warszawa, once a month, until the start of the First World War in 1914. According to Nekrasova (2008, p. 140), stays for lessons lasted a week.
Appearance at a charity concert. Concert mentioned by V. N. Sofronickij (1982, p. 25), who adds a Toccata by Anton Rubinštejn at the start of the program.

Vladimir Sofronickij performed twice at charity concerts, including a performance organized by the English conductor Albert Coates (see Nekrasova 2008, p. 142); the press predicted a brilliant future for the young musician.

First appearance at an open-air concert. According to V. N. Sofronickij (1982, p. 25), this is the charity concert organized by Albert Coates and announced above. Concert criticized in the newspaper Новое время [Novoe vremja]: see V. N. Sofronickij (1982, p. 25), who confirms the program.

Vladimir Sofronickij continued his studies under the supervision of pianist and composer Leonid Aleksandrovič Ščedrin: Sofronickij's mother, who never missed a lesson with Aleksandr Michalovskij, requested Ščedrin's assistance for her son's lessons after the Warszawa period. See Mil’štejn (1982a, p. 422), White (1995, p. 6) and Juban (1998, p. 55).

Due to a cold - or rather because of bad weather - Vladimir Sofronickij misses the opportunity to listen to Skrjabin's last recital, given in Petrograd. It was raining that evening, and young Vladimir was not allowed to leave his house by his parents: “You could catch a cold; it's better to wait until next time. » (Nikonovič 2008b, p. 88.) The composer died two weeks later, on 1915-04-27 (n.s.).

Enrollment at the Petrograd Conservatory, in the piano class of Leonid Nikolaev and in the composition class of Maksimilian Štejnberg, former disciple of Nikolaj Rimskij-Korsakov. Juban (1998, p. 55) instead mentions the date of 1916; Vladimir Sofronickij himself also indicates 1916 as the start of his regular studies at the Petrograd Conservatory (see Mil’štejn 1982a, p. 422). Leonid Nikolaev is a former student of Sergej Taneev and Michail Ippolitov-Ivanov (composition class) and Vasilij Il'ič Safonov (piano class), at the Moskva Conservatory, in the tradition of Teodor Leszetycki. About Leonid Nikolaev and his piano class at the Petrograd Conservatory, see: Al’švang (1939); Bogdanov-Berezovskij (1967b, pp. 70-71); Del’son (1935); Nekrasova (2008, p. 140-142); L. V. Nikolaev (2013); Artese (2000, pp. 5-9 and 85-86); Chkourak (2010); Juban (1998, pp. 55-56); White (1995, p. 6 and 108-111).
Appearance during a musical evening given by students of the conservatory’s higher courses. Artese (2000, p. 7) indicates the first performance of Vladimir Sofronickij in a work with orchestra.
Appearance during a matinee concert given by students from Leonid Nikolaev’s class. Savšinskij (1961, p. 88-89) remembers this master class 3.
Appearance at a charity concert.

Enrollment of Elena Aleksandrovna Skrjabina (1900∘ – 1990†) at the Petrograd Conservatory, in Leonid Nikolaev’s piano class. Elena Aleksandrovna Skrjabina then continued her musical training under the direction of Konstantin Igumnov (see Nekrasova 2008, p. 142).
Participation in a charity concert (Metner, Skrjabin) in which Vera Ivanovna Skrjabina, the composer's widow, took part.
Appearance during a conservatory student evening.
Appearance during a student musical evening.
Participation in the first part of the “Musical Working Day”.
Participation in a charity concert of teachers and students of the conservatory in which Vera Ivanovna Skrjabina takes part.
Participation in the first part of the concert show in favor of the fund of the Orthodox Jewish school of Petrograd.
Concert with works by Liszt, Schumann and Skrjabin.
Participation in an additional concert of the Пролеткульт (proletarian cultural and educational organization).

Vladimir Sofronickij meets the family of the artist Èmil’ Vizel’ (see Nekrasova 2008, p. 144). About Sofronickij and the Vizel’ family, see for example: Gorochovskij (1982); Lobaševa (2003); Vizel’ (2003); Vizel’ (2013b); Vizel’ and Lobaševa (2013); Vizel’ (2013a).
In 1920, the Petrograd House of Arts organized two more concerts by Vladimir Sofronickij, in addition to those indicated; the first was devoted to works by Liszt, the second to works by Schumann.
Participation in a collective concert organized by the district office of precision mechanics factories.
Concert with one or more works by Schumann.

First concert with works by Skrjabin, to commemorate the fifth anniversary of the composer's death (see Nekrasova 2008, p. 142). This concert and that of April 24 had a great impact and contributed greatly to the emerging fame of Vladimir Sofronickij, still a student at the time (see Bogdanov-Berezovskij 1967a). Artese (2000, p. 8) mentions the following program.

Fifty-sixth graduation of the Petrograd Conservatory. Award of the Anton Rubinštejn Prize to Marija Judina and Vladimir Sofronickij. According to tradition since Rubinštejn, Judina and Sofronickij should have each received a grand piano from the Schröder firm, but, due to financial difficulties during those years, the instruments remained “on paper”. About this double state test, see Strel’nikov (1921).

Vladimir Sofronickij met the composer, teacher, musicologist and music critic Valerian Bogdanov-Berezovskij (see Bogdanov-Berezovskij 1967a), but the latter had already been able to listen to the pianist during the Skrjabin concerts in April 1920 in Petrograd.
Appearance during a public ceremony for the 56th promotion of the conservatory.
First appearance with orchestra, under the direction of Èmilij Kuper, as part of a Skrjabin 5 cycle.

Vladimir Sofronickij avoids, as far as possible, concert activities and teaching duties, despite the numerous offers he receives; on the other hand, he devotes himself to the study of new works for his repertoire and to certain technical aspects of his sound and playing (see V. N. Sofronickij 1982, p. 28).

Participation in a symphony concert under the direction of Èmilij Kuper 8 where Vladimir Sofronickij nevertheless plays solo; the conductor of this monographic concert conducts Symphony No. 2 and the Poem of Ecstasy.

Participation in a symphony concert under the direction of Èmilij Kuper. Concert announced in the newspapers Музыка и театр [Muzyka i teatr], n° 20 (May 21, 1923), p. 19; Жизнь искусства [Žizn’ iskusstva], vol. 20, no. 895 (May 22, 1923), p. 28.

Concert or Klavierabend announced by the newspaper Жизнь искусства [Žizn’ iskusstva], vol. 6, no. 980 (February 5, 1924), p. 29. The announcement confirms that Vladimir Sofronickij “has not performed for a long time”. Concert with works by Skrjabin.
Concert absent from the chronology established by Skrjabin and Nikolaeva (2013b, p. 396). A poster nevertheless announces Sofronickij’s “second concert” with works by Skrjabin.
Concert with works by Skrjabin.

Lazarev (2020) presents the poster of a collective concert in which Vladimir Sofronickij participated and which was dedicated to the ninth anniversary of Skrjabin's death. Other musicians also included Konstantin Igumnov and Samuil Fejnberg. Proceeds from the concert were donated to the maintenance of the Skrjabin Museum.
Concert with works by Skrjabin.
Concert with works by Johann Sebastian Bach/Busoni, Liszt and Chopin.

chronology.CE_summary: Concert mentioned in an autograph by Vsevolod Mejerchol’d, dated December 7, 1927 and transcribed by V. N. Sofronickij (1982, p. 31): “[...] [Vladimir Sofronickij] is in music both a thinker and a poet.” Later, in September 1934, Vsevolod Mejerchol’d dedicated his production of Čajkovskij’s The Queen of Spades to Vladimir Sofronickij (see page 10).
Matinee concert 23 (concert no. 4, subscription no. 7).
According to Vizel’, it is rather January 18, 1928. Lazarev (2020) presents a poster which bears the date January 19.
Participation in a symphony concert conducted by Aleksandr Gauk 24 (concert no. 7, subscription no. 6), on the eve of Glazunov's departure.
Additional concert. Farewell concert before the departure of Vladimir Sofronickij to Poland then to France; great success (see Nekrasova 2008, p. 148).

Additional concert. Farewell concert before the departure of Vladimir Sofronickij to Poland then to France; according to Nekrasova (2008, p. 148), it is a repeat of the concert from the day before, given in Leningrad. At the end of this very successful concert, Sofronickij received a message signed by the teachers of the Moskva Conservatory and transcribed by V. N. Sofronickij (1982, p. 31).
Travel abroad by Vladimir Sofronickij and his wife; the trip will take them first to Warszawa in March 1928, and then for a much longer period to Paris from March 1928 to January 1930.
Concert canceled due to the trip abroad undertaken by Vladimir Sofronickij and his wife on March 8, 1928. The program was announced with the following works.

See in particular V. N. Sofronickij (1982, p. 32-33), who mentions the detailed program of the concert. Announced in newspapers and on city posters, the concert was a great success, broadcast via Polish radio stations (see Nekrasova 2008, p. 148).
Meeting of Vladimir Sofronickij with his former teacher, Aleksandr Michalovskij, and the director of the Warszawa Philharmonic Society, Roman Xojnackij (see V. N. Sofronickij 1982, p. 32-33).

According to Nekrasova (2008, p. 148), it was towards the end of March that the Sofronickij couple arrived in Paris, just after this brief stay in Warszawa; White (1995, p. 112) rather indicates the end of April.

Vladimir Sofronickij meets and frequents Nikolaj Karlovič Metner and Sergej Sergeevič Prokof’ev. Sofronickij became a close friend of Prokof'ev and benefited from Metner's advice on piano sound production and the performance of Beethoven's Sonata Appassionata in F minor, opus 57 (see Igor' Nikonovič, translated into English by White 1995, pp. 7-9). In addition, Vladimir Sofronickij had the opportunity to meet or listen to musicians who were then performing on the Parisian scene: Fëdor Ivanovič Šaljapin (Fédor Chaliapin), Titta Ruffo, Iosif (or Jaša) Ruvimovič Rubinstein, Egon Petri, Willem Mengelberg, Bruno Walter, Sergej Rachmaninoff, Walter Gieseking, Vladimir Samojlovič Gorovic (Vladimir Horowitz), Aleksandr Kirillovič Borovskij, Ignacy Jan Paderewski, Leopold Godowsky, Robert Casadesus, Wanda Landowska and many others.

Private concert 25 and first performance in Paris. Present in the room: Sergej Prokof’ev, Aleksandr Kirillovič Borovskij, Boris de Schlœzer (Boris Fëdorovič Šlëcer) and Boris Stepanovič Zaxarov. See page 9.

Letter addressed by Vladimir Sofronickij to the Vizel’ sisters, where the musician indicates that he will play in Paris and Berlin in the fall, and that an engagement in Rome and Amsterdam is being organized, not to mention an invitation to play the Skrjabin Concerto in Paris (see Nekrasova 2008, p. 150); It is possible that we owe to the incompetence of the impresario Lublinsky the fact that Sofronickij will not play outside Paris, and that he will not play there with an orchestra.

According to Skrjabin and Nikolaeva (2013b, p. 400): Chopin room. First public concert in Paris. Concert criticized by Messager 26, Golestan 27, Boris de Schlœzer 28, Tromp 29, Plé 30 and Wolf 31. See page 9.
According to the pianist's son, cited by Skrjabin and Nikolaeva (2013b, p. 400): Chopin room. Second concert. Concert criticized by Golestan 32. See page 9.

Travel of Vladimir Sofronickij and his wife, with Vladimir Dukel'skij and Sergej Prokof'ev, to the Mont-Blanc massif (see Skrjabin and Nikolaeva 2013b, p. 400) and to Switzerland (see Juban 1998, p. 58), passing by the banks of Lake Geneva (see Nekrasova 2008, p. 150); Prokof’ev drives the car (“110 versts per hour”, or 117 km/h). The Sofronickij couple left Paris on July 7, 1928 (see Nikonovič and Skrjabin 2008b, p. 366). A letter from Sofronickij to the Vizel’ sisters, dated August 1, was sent from Saint-Palais-sur-Mer and again evokes peaceful vacations (see Nekrasova 2008, p. 150): the ocean, a pine forest and photographs taken on the beach.
Concert with works by Prokof’ev at the private residence of a wealthy Frenchman, Orcel.
Broadcasting of the Radio Liberté program at 12:30 p.m., the program of which is mentioned by Aymard (1928).

According to Skrjabin and Nikolaeva (2013b, p. 401): Debussy room. The pianist's son indicates the Chopin room. Third concert. Concert announced by Carol-Bérard 33 and criticized by Golestan 34. See page 9.
Fourth concert. Concert announced by Carol-Bérard 35. See page 9.

Letter from Vladimir Sofronickij to Aleksandra Èmil’evna Vizel’ (Ada), where the musician announces his interpretation of Chopin’s Barcarolle in F sharp major, opus 60, which he played for the radio, “Thursday at 12 p.m.”; see Nekrasova (2008, p. 150).

Fifth concert. Concert criticized in detail by Baruzi 36. See page 9. Nekrasova (2008, p. 151) mentions Vers laflamme, opus 72, instead of Poème, opus 32 no. 1, but this is refuted by the detailed report by Baruzi, who attended the concert.
Concert at Dubost.

Concert with Sergej Prokof’ev: the two musicians played, on two pianos, Schubert’s Waltz Suite in Prokof’ev’s transcription. Host of the musicians at the Embassy: Valerian Savel’evič Dovgalevskij (see V. N. Sofronickij 1982, p. 36).

Concert with Sergej Prokof’ev: the two musicians played, on two pianos, Schubert’s Waltz Suite in Prokof’ev’s transcription. See Prokof’ev (2008, pp. 359-360). Host of the musicians at the Embassy: Valerian Savel’evič Dovgalevskij (see V. N. Sofronickij 1982, p. 36).

Sixth concert. Concert criticized by Saint-Astier 37. See page 9. Concert mentioned, as well as the two previous ones with Sergej Prokof'ev, in a letter from Vladimir Sofronickij to Aleksandra Èmil'evna Vizel' (Ada) dated April 7 (see Nekrasova 2008, p. 151).

Concert with works by Prokof’ev at the private residence of a wealthy Frenchman, Orcel. The program included in particular the Sonata in A minor, opus 28, and Fugitive Visions, opus 22. Prokof'ev (2008, p. 360) also mentions the Overture on Jewish Themes in C minor for clarinet, piano and string quartet, opus 34, works for violin, Romances, the Ballade in C minor for cello and piano, opus 15, etc., where Vladimir Sofronickij played the piano part.

According to Skrjabin and Nikolaeva (2013b, p. 401): Debussy room. The pianist's son indicates the Chopin room. Seventh and final concert in Paris; according to those present, a particularly good concert (Nekrasova 2008, p. 151). See page 9.
Resumption of the concert of December 20, 1929 (date uncertain).

Extract from a letter from Vladimir Sofronickij to the Vizel' family, dated December 21: С каждым днем ​​мы все больше и мучительнее тоскуем по родине. In France, however, we do not believe it will be part of the French language. “Every day we yearn more and more painfully for our homeland. France is boring, but we will stay here until the end of January. » (See Nekrasova 2008, p. 151.) Nikonovič (2008b, p. 132) adds that for Vladimir Sofronickij, a Russian cannot live long without Rossija. There could be nothing sadder than emigration.
Vladimir Sofronickij leaves Paris and France.

Return of Vladimir Sofronickij to the Soviet Union, to Leningrad. Elena Aleksandrovna Skrjabina, for her part, remained in France and did not return to the Soviet Union until 1934: she arrived in Moskva in mid-December 1934, then in Leningrad between the end of January and the beginning of February 1935. Bogdanov-Berezovskij (1965, p. 90) evokes the change in the pianist's playing style, after his stay in Poland and France 38.

First concert after returning from France. Concert given by the Персимфанс [Persimfans] with Vladimir Sofronickij as soloist. Nekrasova (2008, p. 152) indicates a performance of Skrjabin's Piano Concerto in F sharp minor, opus 20, with the Persimfans orchestra.
Concert with works by Skrjabin to commemorate the fifteenth anniversary of the composer's death.
Third concert (or Klavierabend) by Vladimir Sofronickij 39 in Leningrad after returning from France.
Concert with works by Chopin for conservatory students.
Concert with works by Chopin. While giving the date May 15 – and not June 15 – Nekrasova (2008, p. 152) indicates the following Chopin program.
Concert for students. Concert unfinished due to heart problems.
Appearance during a symphony concert conducted by Aleksandr Gauk.
Same program as during the concert of October 21, 1930 in Leningrad.
Concert with works by Johann Sebastian Bach, Scarlatti, Chopin, Prokof’ev, Debussy and Skrjabin. According to Aleksandra Èmil’evna Vizel’, it is rather November 22, 1930.
Appearance during a concert of pianists from Leonid Nikolaev’s class.

See in particular Mil’štejn (1982a, p. 444). Skrjabin and Nikolaeva (2013b, p. 402) speak instead of a concert at the great hall of the Moskva Conservatory, which would have been postponed on January 15, 1931; according to Skrjabin and Nikolaeva, the Ballade played would rather be that in F minor, opus 52.
Uncertain concert (Skrjabin and Nikolaeva 2013b, p. 402).

Joint concert by Vladimir Sofronickij and Marija Judina (precise date unknown and location not specified; see Skrjabin and Nikolaeva (2013b, p. 403)).
Joint concert by Vladimir Sofronickij and Genrich Nejgauz.

Series of concerts in Tbilisi, on the initiative of Marija Judina who, at the time, often performed in Georgia. Some solo concerts, others in common with Marija Judina. Travel with Èmil’ Vizel’ and his eldest daughter Aleksandra Èmil’evna Vizel’ (Ada); During the train journey and during concert rehearsals in Tbilisi, Èmil’ Vizel’ made numerous “live” sketches of Vladimir Sofronickij, some of which have been preserved to this day. See Nekrasova (2008, p. 152 and 153) and Mil’štejn (1982a, p. 427).

and 1932-10 Toškent. Several concerts – five, according to Nekrasova (2008, p. 155). In a letter to his son A. V. Sofronickij (1982, p. 44), Vladimir Sofronickij indicates that he was invited to the Toškent observatory: he was able to observe the Moon (“800 times magnification”), Saturn, the Andromeda [galaxy] (Messier 31), Vega (α Lyrae) and other celestial bodies. He left “absolutely stunned”. A. V. Sofronickij (1982, p. 44) gives the date of October 6, 1930 for this letter from Toškent, but it is undoubtedly 1932.

During the 1937-1938 season, at the Leningrad Conservatory, Vladimir Sofronickij announced a cycle of twelve concerts with different programs. This cycle of recitals, at the “height of Stalinist terror” (Voskobojnikov 2009b, p. 540), had a great impact, comparable to that of the seven “historical concerts” given by Anton Rubinštejn in Rossija, in Europe and in the United States of America, in the 19th century. See, in particular, an article by L. Poljuta and L. Potexin 45 transcribed by Mil’štejn (1982a, p. 430) then by Nikonovič and Skrjabin (2008a, p. 387-388) and an article by V. Bogdanov-Berezovskij 46 transcribed by Mil’štejn (1982a, p. 430-431). See also V. N. Sofronickij (1982, pp. 38-41).

First concert of the cycle of twelve “historical concerts”. Nekrasova (2008, p. 158) and Voskobojnikov (2009b, p. 541) give the date December 11, 1937, while White (1995, p. 48), Artese (2000, p. 16) and Skrjabin and Nikolaeva (2013b, p. 410-411) give the date December 1 1937, as did Sofronickij in a letter dated October 20, 1937 to his family (Kogan 2008, p. 20).
Second concert of the cycle. Concert mentioned, as well as the following one, in a letter dated December 17, 1937 from Vladimir Sofronickij to his family (Kogan 2008, p. 21).
Third concert of the cycle. The Vladimir Sofronickij cycle continues until June 1938.
Fourth concert of the cycle. This concert did not take place: concert postponed to January 20.

For the jubilee of the Leningrad Conservatory, Vladimir Sofronickij plays Anton Rubinštejn's Concerto in D minor, opus 70. The symphony orchestra is under the direction of Isaj Moiseevič Al'terman, a disciple of Aleksandr Gauk.
Fourth concert of the cycle. Concert postponed from January 6; program indicated above.

Fifth concert of the cycle. Skrjabin and Nikolaeva (2013b, p. 411) indicate the date of January 28 for this concert initially scheduled for January 24 (see Nekrasova 2008, p. 158). According to Nekrasova, Liszt's first performed work, in E minor, is not specified.

Sixth concert of the cycle. Nekrasova (2008, p. 158) and Skrjabin and Nikolaeva (2013b, p. 411) give the date February 8, 1938, while White (1995, p. 49) gives February 2, 1938. The most recent reference mentions that the concert was postponed from February 2.

Twelfth and final concert of the cycle. Nekrasova (2008, p. 159) and Skrjabin and Nikolaeva (2013b, p. 412) give the date June 21, 1938, while White (1995, p. 50) gives June 8, 1938. The most recent reference mentions that the concert was postponed from June 8. Concert and cycle mentioned by Vladimir Sofronickij in a letter to his family on June 22, 1938 (Kogan 2008, p. 24). Regarding Mjaskovskij's performed works, Nekrasova (2008, p. 159) rather indicates Two Причуды [Pričudy], that is to say Two Eccentricities, taken from opus 25. Still according to Nekrasova, Prokof'ev's performed works were rather: Legend, opus 12 no. 6; Tales of the Old Grandmother, opus 31; Two Steps; Gavotte; Sonata No. 3 in A minor, opus 28. See Bogdanov-Berezovskij (1967a) for performed works by this composer.

For the 1938-1939 season, announcement of the project for a cycle of concerts devoted to Russian and Soviet music, and given in the great hall of the Leningrad Philharmonic Society. The first concert of the cycle took place on November 28, 1938. Dates of the following concerts: December 20, 1938, January 31, 1939, April 21, 1939 and May 7, 1939. Composers performed during this cycle: Dmitrij Bortnjanskij, Michail Glinka, Modest Musorgskij, Aleksandr Borodin, Anton Rubinštejn, Pëtr Čajkovskij, Milij Balakirev, Sergej Ljapunov, Anatolij Ljadov, Aleksandr Glazunov, Anatolij Aleksandrov, Samuil Fejnberg, Nikolaj Mjaskovskij, Vladimir Ščerbačëv, Dmitrij Kabalevskij and other authors. Some concerts of the cycle were repeated in Moskva. See Nekrasova (2008, p. 160) and Skrjabin and Nikolaeva (2013b, p. 413).
Concert with works by Soviet composers; first concert of the cycle announced above.

Start of the Great Patriotic War (or Eastern Front of the Second World War), following the Barbarossa invasion operation of the Third Reich in the Soviet Union. Vladimir Sofronickij gave more than forty solo concerts during the war years, from autumn 1941 to spring 1945 (Nekrasova 2008, p. 167).

Vladimir Sofronickij resides at the Leningrad Conservatory. On July 29, 1941, Dmitrij Šostakovič and Vladimir Sofronickij were photographed on the roofs of the conservatory, in firefighter outfits, for the newspapers. Letters from the pianist to his family on July 27 and 29, 1941 (Kogan 2008, p. 31).
Start of the siege of Leningrad.

Evening at the home of Valerian Bogdanov-Berezovskij. Igor’ Miklaševskij and other musicians are present, including the composer Vladimir Mixajlovič Deševov (see Bogdanov-Berezovskij 1967a). In a letter to his wife, Vladimir Sofronickij said: "I play a lot and well..." Leonid Abramovič Portov, quoted by A. V. Sofronickij (2013b, p. 202-203), mentions the following program, played by Sofronickij (Bogdanov-Berezovskij instead mentions pieces by Prokof'ev, Skrjabin, Schumann and Debussy).

Vladimir Sofronickij moved to the lower floor of the Puškin Theater, where many artists who had not yet left lived, in particular Daniil Šafran and Dmitrij Šostakovič. See Juban (1998, p. 58). Nekrasova (2008, p. 165) indicates the month of October, rather than September.

Concert interrupted due to bombing. Descent of the public and the musician to safety. Then, extended curfew then resumption of the concert (see Nekrasova 2008, p. 164). Savkevič (1982, p. 342), cited by A. V. Sofronickij (2013b, p. 203), specifies that the concert was interrupted in the middle of Chopin Studies.
Concert for the defenders of besieged Leningrad. This is the concert mentioned by V. V. Sofronickij (1942, 1961) himself.

Siege of Leningrad. Vladimir Sofronickij admitted to the hospital, located within the walls of the Astoria Hotel, where victims of famine and cold were treated. Without giving a precise date, Jurij Lazarevič Aljanskij, cited by A. V. Sofronickij (2013b, p. 204), indicates that Vladimir Sofronickij sometimes played the piano at the Astoria hotel, for around ten or fifteen minutes at most – he played Skrjabin or Rachmaninoff, Liszt or Chopin, in the dark; bedridden patients listened to him there. Testimony confirmed by that of Andrej Nikolaevič Krjukov (see A. V. Sofronickij 2013b, p. 204).
Death of Vladimir Sofronickij's father in Leningrad.

Vladimir Sofronickij receives from Boris Ivanovič Zagurskij (head of the artistic department of the executive committee of the city of Leningrad) the announcement of his imminent evacuation, a priori by road and rail, planned for the very first days of April (Nekrasova 2008, p. 165). Farewell by Vladimir Sofronickij to his great friend Ekaterina Daugovet (1882∘ – 1942†), pianist and teacher at the Leningrad Conservatory, too weakened to be saved (Nekrasova 2008, p. 165-166).
Vladimir Sofronickij, evacuated by airlift from besieged Leningrad, arrives in Moskva.
Vladimir Sofronickij's first concert in Moskva after his evacuation from Leningrad. See Žukova (1982, p. 301) and Žukova (2008, p. 216).
Vladimir Sofronickij's second concert in Moskva after his evacuation from Leningrad; second program.
Vladimir Sofronickij's third concert in Moskva after his evacuation from Leningrad; third different program.

Philharmonic concert. See in particular Mil’štejn (1982a, p. 442) and Nikonovič and Skrjabin (2008a, p. 393).

The magazine Sovetskaja muzyka 49 reproduces a letter allegedly written and sent by Vladimir Sofronickij to the editor of the Daily Express newspaper in London: its subject is the duty of the artist in times of war and the siege of Leningrad. This letter and several others, written by other Russian musicians, are introduced and presented by Krasil’ščik (1980), editor-in-chief of the Novosti press agency.
Philharmonic Concert 50. See in particular Mil’štejn (1982a, p. 442) and Nikonovič and Skrjabin (2008a, p. 393).

Beginning of the educational work of Vladimir Sofronickij at the Moskva Conservatory (teacher of the piano class). Žukova (2008, p. 214) indicates the month of December 1942 instead.

In the newspaper Литература и искусство [Literatura i iskusstvo], publication of an article written by Vladimir Sofronickij and entitled: “The duty of the artist”. See also V. V. Sofronickij (1961). This is a speech given by the pianist to the audience at the Puškin Theater in Leningrad in December 1941, during the siege of the city. Skrjabin and Nikolaeva (2013b, p. 420) indicate November 4th rather than November 7th.

Joint concert with Dmitrij Žuravlev (reciter). Concert with works by Prokof’ev, Šostakovič and Skrjabin. Lazarev (2020) presents a note from Vladimir Sofronickij and Dmitrij Žuravlev discussing their concert for the defenders of Leningrad 54.
See in particular Mil’štejn (1982a, p. 442) and Nikonovič and Skrjabin (2008a, p. 394).

Awarding of the first grade Stalin Prize to Vladimir Sofronickij, for exceptional achievements in concert and in the performing arts. Lazarev (2020) presents an article by I. Martynov 55 which discusses this attribution; see also Zagurskij (1943).

According to Skrjabin and Nikolaeva (2013b, p. 423), Vladimir Sofronickij’s stay in Berlin lasted from July 20, 1945 to July 28, 1945 and there were three concerts, with the participation of Vladimir Sofronickij, Èmil’ Gilel’s, Galina Barinova and Aleksandr Dedjuchin, in front of the leaders of the anti-Nazi coalition. According to Roksana Kogan-Sofronicaja, on the other hand, the stay in Potsdam lasted only three days (Artese 2000, p. 95). Nekrasova (2008, p. 166 and 167) confirms Sofronickij's three concerts in Berlin and Potsdam, as well as the stay from August 20 to 28 [sic] (letter to Aleksandra Èmil'evna Vizel' dated September 2, 1945).

– 1949-12 Despite his health problems, Vladimir Sofronickij presents a cycle of five concerts for the hundredth anniversary of Chopin's death. Concert dates: October 20 and 29; November 21; December 19 and 24. The programs included the Two Sonatas (opus 35 and 58), the Four Ballads, the Four Scherzos, the Twenty-four Preludes (opus 28), twelve Études, thirty Mazurkas, six Waltzes, six Nocturnes, Impromptus, the Fantasy in F minor, opus 49, the Barcarolle in F sharp major, opus 60, the Tarantella in A flat major, opus 43, the concert Allegro in A major, opus 46, six Polonaises and other works 69 (see Nekrasova 2008, p. 170).

First concert of the Chopin cycle to commemorate the hundredth anniversary of the composer's death. Concert recorded in part. The period 1955-1958 includes all the editorial work of Vladimir Sofronickij, who devotes part of his time to it, while he only plays at the Skrjabin Museum and in other small concert halls. He thus worked on the edition of the piano works of the following composers: Aleksandr Skrjabin (Eight Studies, opus 42, in 1955; Third Sonata in F sharp minor, opus 23, in 1956; Fourth Sonata in F sharp major, opus 30, in 1957; Waltz in A flat major, opus 38, in 1957; Three Études, opus 65, in 1957), Nikolaj Metner (Sonata in G minor, opus 22, in 1957; Triade of Sonatas, opus 11, in 1958) and Maurice Ravel (Works for piano, in two volumes, in 1958-1962). All these editions were published by the Moscow department of Музгиз [Muzgiz], the state music publishing house. See Nikonovič (2008b, p. 126 and footnote).

Concert with works by Prokof’ev. Perhaps Sonata No. 7 in B flat major, opus 83: before the concert, Vladimir Sofronickij played a memorable Seventh Sonata at his home for Varvara Nekrasova and her husband (see Nekrasova 2008, p. 180).

Shortly after this concert on March 14, Vladimir Sofronickij fell seriously ill with his heart; see Širjaeva (1982, p. 379-380) and Nekrasova (2008, p. 181). Nina Grigor’evna Širjaeva and Aleksandra Èmil’evna Vizel’ stayed at his bedside for almost two months. His health only began to improve during the second half of May, a slow improvement until summer (see Širjaeva 1982, p. 411).
Concert recorded in part.
Vladimir Sofronickij, on leave, does not go to the Moskva conservatory; he tells Širjaeva (1982, p. 416) that he finally feels “like an artist, happy to be able to think only about music”.
See Širjaeva (1982, p. 396) regarding the works of Johann Sebastian Bach performed.
Resumption of the program of the concert of September 26, but with several modifications according to Nekrasova (2008, p. 182).

See in particular Mil’štejn (1982a, p. 446). Nekrasova (2008, p. 181), based on the archives of Aleksandra Èmil’evna Vizel’, also mentions a recital with the program below, at the House of Scientists.
Concert with works by Schumann.
Concert with works by Schumann, recorded in full. See in particular Mil’štejn (1982a, p. 446).
See in particular Mil’štejn (1982a, p. 446-447).
Nekrasova (2008, p. 181) mentions this date for a concert by Vladimir Sofronickij, but indicates that this date and that of November 30 only appear in the archives of Aleksandra Èmil’evna Vizel’.

Concert recorded in large part. There may still be some doubt about the exact date of this recital (see ADGO 2021a). Most references give this date as January 6, 1960: see Mil’štejn (1982a, p. 461), Evans (2008), Nikonovič (2011, p. 23), Skrjabin and Nikolaeva (2013b, p. 442) and, in particular, Nekrasova (2008, p. 182). In her 1995 article, Nekrasova, on the other hand, gives the date of the following day, January 7, 1960 (see Nekrasova 1995). In the discography and below, I have stuck to the most recent publication of Varvara Nekrasova, who received the correspondence maintained by Vladimir Sofronickij and Aleksandra Èmil’evna Vizel’. The list below complements Skrjabin and Nikolaeva (2013b, p. 442) thanks to the census of recorded works (see Nikonovič 2011, p. 23 and 30). According to Skrjabin and Nikolaeva (2013b, p. 442), the second part of the recital began with Opus 52 No. 1.

Concert with works by Skrjabin, partly recorded and broadcast; Vladimir Sofronickij himself indicated 75 that only the first part of the recital was broadcast, and not the second. Malik's work in 1998 helped to resolve the uncertainties between the concert of January 8, 1960 and that of February 2, 1960, based on their first editions on vinyl records. Concert program found by ADGO (2021a), with corrections made by hand to the printed program and which partly contradict the program indications given by Nekrasova (2008, p. 182). See table 25.1 on page 35.
Birth of Viviana Sofronickaja-Dušinova.

Nekrasova (2008, p. 183), citing the personal archives of Aleksandra Èmil’evna Vizel’, mentions this date for a concert by Vladimir Sofronickij; the archives, however, indicate neither the location nor the program.

Recording for radio. Vladimir Sofronickij records works by Chopin: Polonaise in C sharp minor, opus 26 no. 1; Four Mazurkas; Fantasy ; Nocturne No. 8 in D flat major, Opus 27 No. 2; Ballad No. 3 in A flat major, opus 47.
Recording (20 to 24 hours) of works by Chopin: Polonaise in C sharp minor, opus 26 no. 1; Five Mazurkas. Total recorded time: 27 minutes.
Resumption of recording from January 21.

Nekrasova (2008, p. 183), citing the personal archives of Aleksandra Èmil’evna Vizel’, mentions this date for a concert by Vladimir Sofronickij; the archives, however, indicate neither the location nor the program.

Concert with works by Skrjabin, recorded at least in part. Malik's work in 1998 helped to resolve the uncertainties between the concert of January 8, 1960 and that of February 2, 1960, based on their first editions on vinyl records. See in particular Mil’štejn (1982a, p. 447). Almost all authors indicate a program dedicated to Skrjabin, but Nekrasova (2008, p. 183) states that the first part of the recital consisted of works by Chopin and the second of compositions by Skrjabin (this is undoubtedly an error on Nekrasova's part). See table 25.1 on page 35.

In a letter dated April 18 (see Nekrasova 2008, p. 184), Vladimir Sofronickij indicates that health reasons led him to cancel a stay in Poland, where he should have gone during the month of March 1960 to play. It is possible that this planned but canceled trip was that of Warszawa mentioned by Voskobojnikov (2008) towards the end of the second broadcast of his cycle devoted to the pianist: it was a celebration of the 150th anniversary of Chopin's birth, for which the Polish authorities had requested the presence of Sofronickij.
Concert and program indicated by Nekrasova (2008, p. 183) and found by ADGO (2021a).
Nekrasova (2008, p. 184) mentions this recital, the program of which does not appear in the archives kept by Aleksandra Èmil’evna Vizel’.

Vladimir Sofronickij contacted by the editorial team of the newspaper Советский Союз [Sovetskij Sojuz], in order to write an article about the music of Robert Schumann, on the occasion of the 150th anniversary of the composer's birth; a preliminary draft of the article is reproduced by Širjaeva (1982, pp. 386-387). The final text of Sofronickij's article on Schumann in the journal Советский Союз, published in June 1960, is transcribed by Mil'štejn (1982a, p. 447-448).
Concert with works by Skrjabin, according to Skrjabin and Nikolaeva (2013b, p. 443). According to Nekrasova (2008, p. 184), on the other hand, the program was as follows.

Concert mentioned by Vladimir Sofronickij, in a letter dated the same day (see Nekrasova 2008, p. 184). A concert by Sofronickij in the large hall of the conservatory, at this time of his life, is quite surprising (Juban 1998, p. 59), but the rest of the letter mentions a rehearsal for exams, after the concert but on the same evening, in the small hall which had been his preference since 1955. Nekrasova (2008, p. 184) adds that this concert is not mentioned either in the chronology established by Mil'štejn (1982a, p. 455-461), nor in the archives of Aleksandra Èmil’evna Vizel’; it is still absent from the chronology established by Skrjabin and Nikolaeva (2013b, p. 443).
Concert with works by Liszt.
Concert with works by Skrjabin. See in particular Panarin (1982, p. 372-376).

Concert recorded in large part. In addition to the recorded works, it appears that Skrjabin's Etude in D sharp minor, opus 8 no. 12, was also performed at this concert, at the end of the encores (White 1995, p. 69). See in particular Mil’štejn (1982a, p. 447).
Concert with works by Chopin, to commemorate the 150th anniversary of the composer's birth. Program indicated by Nekrasova (2008, p. 185).
Concert with works by Skrjabin, to commemorate the 45th anniversary of the composer's death. Concert and program indicated by Nekrasova (2008, p. 185) and found by ADGO (2021a).
Concert recorded in part.

Concert with works by Schumann, to commemorate the 150th anniversary of the composer's birth. Concert program indicated by Nekrasova (2008, p. 185) and found by ADGO (2021a); see also Širjaeva (1982, p. 387) for the last three works mentioned in the program below.
Nekrasova (2008, p. 185) mentions this date for a concert by Vladimir Sofronickij. The program has not been preserved, but the date is taken from the museum files.
Concert recorded in part.

Concert recorded in part. Skrjabin's first three works are mentioned by Johansson (2016, p. 13). Nekrasova (2008, p. 186) indicates a permuted order, with the first part devoted to Skrjabin and the second to Chopin; she also mentions that the interpretation of Chopin’s Nocturne in E flat major was “a real revelation”.

Nekrasova (2008, p. 188) mentions a recording session, at the museum, with the same program as that of the previous concert; the session lasted three hours, which were the last during which Nekrasova was able to listen to Sofronickij playing live.
Concert recorded in part. The two pieces taken from opus 56 are mentioned by Johansson (2016, p. 13).

Meeting of Vladimir Sofronickij and Van Cliburn 76 (see for example Širjaeva 1982, p. 399-403). In 1958, Van Cliburn won first prize in the first international Pëtr Čajkovskij competition in Moskva. In a letter dated August 2, 1960, Vladimir Sofronickij recalls for Aleksandra Èmil'evna Vizel' his meeting with Van Cliburn and indicates that the works they played for each other on this occasion were recorded on tape (see Nekrasova 2008, p. 188).
See in particular Mil’štejn (1982a, p. 451).

Nekrasova (2008, p. 188) mentions this date for a concert by Vladimir Sofronickij. The program is not known, but the date is taken from the archives of Aleksandra Èmil’evna Vizel’ and confirmed by the museum.
Same program as September 19, 1960.
Concert recorded in part. See in particular Mil’štejn (1982a, p. 451).
Concert recorded in part. See in particular Mil’štejn (1982a, p. 451). Same program as October 11, 1960.

Concert recorded in part. See in particular Mil’štejn (1982a, p. 451-452). According to the program for this recital, found by ADGO (2021a), Chopin's Ballade, opus 47, was not played this evening, and instead we find six Études (three from opus 10, three from opus 25).

Concert recorded in part. See in particular Mil’štejn (1982a, p. 451-452). Same program as October 22, 1960. Mil’štejn (1982a, p. 452) mentions the Sonetto 123 del Petrarca, in place of the Sonetto 104 del Petrarca, for this evening’s recital.

See in particular Mil’štejn (1982a, p. 452). According to the program for this recital, found by ADGO (2021a), an additional work by Liszt, the Canzonetta del Salvator Rosa, S 161 no. 3, would also have been performed.
Concert and program found by ADGO (2021a).

See in particular Mil’štejn (1982a, p. 440 and p. 452). Recital mentioned and criticized by Rabinovič (1961a, p. 138-139), under the pseudonym Florestan. Nekrasova (2008, p. 189) only mentions opuses 27 and 43 for Chopin's works.

This concert should have taken place on November 20, but it was rescheduled (ADGO 2021a). Last concert as a soloist at the Moskva Conservatory. See in particular Mil’štejn (1982a, p. 441 and p. 452). Subsequently, Vladimir Sofronickij's work resumed at the Moskva Conservatory, and he therefore indicated that he did not know when his next concert would take place (see Širjaeva 1982, p. 416).
Last studio recording session.
Concert recorded in part.

Last concert at the Skrjabin Museum, partly recorded. See in particular Badejan (2008, p. 354). Nikonovič (2008b, p. 105) indicates that Genrich Nejgauz was present at the Skrjabin Museum for this concert by Vladimir Sofronickij.
Nekrasova (2008, p. 190) mentions that concerts by Vladimir Sofronickij were announced for February 19 and 21, 1961, but that they did not take place, due to the progressing illness.

For the eighth anniversary of the composer's death, Vladimir Sofronickij had planned a concert dedicated to the music of Sergej Prokof'ev; the concert was canceled due to illness (see Širjaeva 1982, p. 393). The pianist worked in particular on pieces from the Roméo et Juliette Suite, opus 75.
Last letter from Vladimir Sofronickij to Aleksandra Èmil’evna Vizel’, where he informs her in particular that her concert scheduled for April 23 is in danger of cancellation.
Publication of an article by Genrich Nejgauz 77 devoted to Vladimir Sofronickij, ending with these words: Слава ему, бесподобному поэту фортепиано! “Glory to him, incomparable poet of the piano! »
Last meeting of Igor’ Nikonovič with Vladimir Sofronickij (see Nikonovič 2008b, p. 113).

Official announcement of support for the request of the Moskva Conservatory for the award of the honorary title “People's Artist of the RSFSR” (Rossija Soviet Federative Socialist Republic) to Vladimir Sofronickij.
Death of Vladimir Sofronickij in Moskva, around 3:35 a.m. (see A. V. Sofronickij 1982, p. 65).
Burial at the Novodevič’e cemetery in Moskva (sector 8 [13] 155), after a tribute ceremony in the small hall of the conservatory (see Zolotov 2008, p. 325).

label: Le Chant du monde
release.CE_note: Disque publié en 1985. La maison d’édition Le Chant du monde a publié le double disque vinyle LDX 78764/5 consacré à Skrjabin (Sonate opus 19 [premier mouvement seul], Sonate opus 23, Sonate opus 30, Sonate opus 53, Sonate opus 66, Sonate opus 68, Sonate opus 70 et enregistrement intégral des Études opus 8). Les mêmes versions des Sonates, sauf l’opus 19 datée 1960-12-11, ont été reprises sur le disque compact Le Chant du monde LDC 278764 ; les mêmes versions des Études ont été reprises sur le disque compact Le Chant du monde LDC 278765, en couplage avec un enregistrement intégral entre 1950 et 1960 des Préludes opus 11.

label: Harmonia Mundi
release.CE_note: Disque publié en 1986. La maison d’édition Harmonia Mundi a publié le disque vinyle HMC 5169 consacré à Schubert (Sonate D 960) et à cinq lieder de Schubert transcrits par Liszt (Aufenthalt, Der Doppelgänger, Erlkönig, Frühlingsglaube et Der Müller und der Bach). Les mêmes versions de ces œuvres ont été reprises sur le disque compact Harmonia Mundi HMX 1905169.

label: CRQ Editions
release.CE_about:
Preludes, Poems, Mazurkas and Ninth Sonata by Alexander Scriabin
The great Russian pianist Vladmimir Sofronitzky was married to Scriabin's daughter who considered him to be the most authentic interpreter of her father's music. This recital, recorded live in 1960, was first issued on LP by Melodya

composition.note:
Il n’existe qu’un seul enregistrement connu de cette Étude par Vladimir Sofronickij (voir ci-dessous). En l’absence d’informations de la part de l’éditeur (lieu et date d’enregistrement, provenance de la source, etc.), l’édition Profil Hänssler PH22006 (disque 1, plage 14) ne peut donc pas être incluse ici.
Remarque.– Le seul enregistrement connu de cette Étude par Vladimir Sofronickij provient d’un récital au musée Skrjabin le 30 décembre 1957 : voir Nikonovič (2011, p. 28) et Skrjabin et Nikolaeva (2013b, p. 391). L’enregistrement a été publié par le musée Skrjabin sous la forme d’un fichier MP3 (release no. 2, track 14).
